data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, the code would benefit from modernization using `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you better thread pool usage and built-in support for cancellation via `CancellationToken` if you need it later. But it's an improvement, not a required migration step.
